{"ts":"2026-06-27T17:41:52.830Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Prioritizing the Design**\n\nI'm focusing on the design phase now, recognizing it's the right starting point. I've decided to create a plan before getting into code changes. I'm starting with a Page or Section Narrative, specifically for the Admin Clients Page, or /admin/clients. This is the Enclave Tenant Registry, and its purpose is to list entities provisioned onto the GFF AI platform.\n\n\n**Defining the UI Elements**\n\nI'm now diving into the user interface elements for both the `/admin/clients` and `/admin/users` pages. For clients, I envision hardware partition locks, PKI seals, and eBPF sockets as the visual metaphor. User pages will be high-clearance security badges. This will help inform the premium typography I am aiming for. I'm also planning the layout strategy, considering a premium stats grid, search bars, and a sortable table for the admin clients page.\n\n\n**Refining the Interactions**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the micro-interactions and transitions for the admin views. Specifically, I'm aiming for an Apple-inspired table for the clients page, complete with hover effects and slide-out detail drawers, edit modals, and a creation modal. On the admin users page, I'm thinking of a role stats badge header, search bar, and a grid of badge-styled cards showing user roles, email, clearance, and status, with interactive action buttons and simple modal forms for invite/edit. This will need full integration of loading, error, and validation states, and a subtle reload animation, all smoothly transitioned with CSS.\n\n**Adapting for Mobile**\n\nNow I'm looking at mobile responsiveness. My strategy involves collapsing grid elements into single columns on smaller screens. I'll need to make drawer sizes responsive as well, and use overflow scrolls for tables with prioritized columns on smaller screens.\n\n**Defining the Implementation**\n\nI've determined the files that I need to edit. I need to connect `/app/admin/clients/page.tsx` to the `/api/v1/clients` backend CRUD, including error, loading, and success states, and I will be restricting access/creation based on the `/api/v1/auth/me` user role.\n\n\n**Clarifying Backend Connections**\n\nI'm now connecting `/app/admin/users/page.tsx` to the backend `/api/v1/users` endpoints, managing loading, success, error, and retry states. Access will be restricted by user role, matching the `/api/v1/auth/me` user role for edit and deactivation privileges.\nI'm also looking at which files I should *not* touch; for example, landing page assets.\n\nI'm checking how user roles and clearances are enforced in the client-side UI, pulling in user profile data from `/api/v1/auth/me`. I will store it as `currentUser` state. Client side role visibility will be enforced according to the current user role on the backend.\n\n\n**Enforcing Access Restrictions**\n\nNow I'm focusing on granular access control based on user roles (e.g., `gff_admin`, `support_agent`, `viewer`). For clients, only `gff_admin` should see the \"Register New Enclave Tenant\" button. Likewise, the \"Provision New Identity Credentials\" button should be hidden from non-admins. Edit and deactivation actions on both clients and users are restricted to `gff_admin`. I'm also double-checking token fetching in `app/admin/dashboard/page.tsx` for silent login handling.\n\n\n"}}
